Biography


Selected Matters


News







Stephen S. Rabinowitz focuses his practice in the field of patent litigation with an emphasis on the life sciences, particularly pharmaceuticals and biotechnology. He has litigated patent cases concerning recombinant DNA technology, nucleic acid amplification, proteins, medical diagnostics, dietary supplements and pharmaceuticals, including in Hatch-Waxman actions arising from Abbreviated New Drug Applications with Paragraph IV certifications. In addition to receiving his J.D. from Harvard Law School and his M.B., Ch.B. from the University of Cape Town, Stephen completed his medical training and internship at Groote Schuur Hospital in Cape Town. He then performed research at the Sir William Dunn School of Pathology and Balliol College, University of Oxford, where he received a D.Phil. in immunology. He was a pathology resident at the Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Harvard Medical School.Professional ActivitiesMember, American Bar AssociationMember, New York Intellectual Property AssociationMember, Association of the Bar of the City of New YorkPrevious ExperiencePartner, Fried Frank, 2004 – 2014Partner, Pennie & Edmonds LLP, 2001 – 2003RecognitionRecognized by Chambers USA as a leading individual in Intellectual Property – PatentsRecognized by Benchmark: Litigation as a National Litigation Star and a New York Litigation StarSpeaking Engagements“Preparing for the Impending Reality of Biosimilars Patent Litigation: Immediate Action Plans for the First Wave,” American Conference Institute, June 7, 2013“Evolving Theories of Inducement and Divided Infringement in Paragraph IV Litigation Concerning Method Treatment Patents,” American Conference Institute, Oct. 4, 2013Court AdmissionsSupreme Court of the United StatesCourt of Appeals for the Federal CircuitFederal District Courts in New York, California and the District of ColumbiaUnited States Patent & Trademark Office


Highlighted MattersGenentech Inc. v. Apotex Inc., No. 3:11-cv-02410-JSW (N.D. Cal. March 10, 2014) Counsel for plaintiffs in Hatch-Waxman action concerning antiviral pharmaceutical Valcyte; defeated a motion for summary judgment of noninfringementCepheid v. Roche Molecular Systems Inc., No. 3:12-cv-4411-EMC (N.D. Cal. Jan. 17, 2013) Counsel for claimant in international arbitration concerning polymerase chain reaction (PCR) technology; obtained a stay of parallel declaratory judgment action under the Federal Arbitration ActGilead Sciences Inc. v. Merck & Co. Inc., No. 5:13-cv-04057-BLF (N.D. Cal.) Counsel for patent-owners and counterclaimants in a declaratory judgment action concerning pharmaceutical for treatment of Hepatitis C Virus (HCV) infection In re Hoffmann-La Roche Inc., 587 F.3d 1333 (Fed. Cir. 2009) Obtained writ of mandamus directing transfer, from the Eastern District of Texas, of a patent infringement action concerning a pharmaceutical for treatment of HIV infectionCarnegie Mellon University v. Hoffmann-La Roche Inc., 541 F.3d 1115 (Fed. Cir. 2008) Arguing counsel for prevailing defendants/appellees in a patent infringement action concerning plasmids for expressing recombinant DNA polymerase enzymes; all 72 asserted claims held not infringed or invalid for lack of written description


 Litigation Roundup: Fourth Quarter 2016  HHR Advisories & Publications | Finance, Restructuring and Bankruptcy | Intellectual Property | Litigation, Arbitration and Investigations | Deals & Matters  View News Article  Firm Deepens Patent Litigation Team with  Partners James W. Dabney and Stephen S. Rabinowitz  News & Events | Intellectual Property | People  View News Article 






